Englefield's nephew, namesake, and eventual heir, Sir Francis Englefield (c. 1561 – 26 October 1631), who became the [1st Baronet Englefield](/Englefield_Baronets), further cemented the family's standing through his marriage. He married Jane Browne, who was the daughter of Anthony Browne (22 July 1552 – 29 June 1592) and Mary Dormer, the daughter of [Sir William Dormer](/William_Dormer) (died 1575). This Jane Browne held notable familial connections: she was the niece of [Mary Wriothesley, Countess of Southampton](/Mary_Wriothesley,_Countess_of_Southampton) (22 July 1552 – 4 November 1607), and the granddaughter of [Anthony Browne, 1st Viscount Montagu](/Anthony_Browne,_1st_Viscount_Montagu) (died 19 October 1592) by his first wife, [Jane Radcliffe](/Jane_Browne,_Viscountess_Montague). These connections illustrate the enduring power of dynastic marriages within the English aristocracy, even as the religious and political landscape continued its tumultuous evolution.

